# Cursor Rules
# These rules guide Cursor's AI when generating commit messages.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# Commit Message Generation Rules
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
when generating commit messages:
  - Always use **conventional commit** style. Do not include any types in the '<type>:' that is not one of the following:
      • feature → for new functionality
      • fix → for bug fixes
      • docs → for documentation changes
      • refactor → for code restructuring without behavior change
      • test → for adding or updating tests
      • chore → for build or maintenance changes
      • performance → for performance improvements (can be functional performance increase - capability improvement, or compute performance increase - speed of computation)
  - Format should be:  
    `<type>: <concise, lowercase description>`
  - Example:  
    `feature: adding new lambda function for metadata extraction`
  - Use all lowercase for the entire commit message.
  - Keep the subject line under 70 characters.
  - Do not include punctuation at the end of the line (no periods).
  - Avoid unnecessary adjectives; focus on what changed, not why.
  - If the change introduces an incompatible or breaking modification,
    append a `BREAKING CHANGE:` section in the body, describing what changed and required actions.
  - Do not include ticket IDs, emojis, or extra formatting.

# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
# Example Commit Messages (for pattern reference)
# ──────────────────────────────────────────────
examples:
  - "feature: adding new lambda function for metadata extraction"
  - "fix: resolving timeout issue in batch job invocation"
  - "refactor: reorganizing dynamodb query helpers"
  - "docs: updating deployment instructions in readme"
  - "test: adding unit tests for concurrency lambda"
  - "chore: bumping dependencies and cleanup scripts"
  - |
    "feature: updating api response schema
     BREAKING CHANGE: endpoint /v1/listings now requires 'listing_id' parameter"